    <section id="START">

        <text>
            The diagram in Figure 1 is similar to many you will work with in Statics.  
            The L-shaped post models a common structure used to support traffic signals and large road signs.  
            Note the orientation of the coordinate system with origin at point A and how dimensional information is 
            given both as dimension annotations and point coordinates.  For example, the dimension a is the length of 
            the horizontal part of the post (from the centerline of the vertical part to the connection at B) and is 
            parallel to the x-axis.
            \n\nThe coordinates (X_C, Y_C, 0) give the position of point C, which is the center 
            of the bottom of the post base.
            \n\nThe coordinates (0, 0, 0) give the position of point A, which is the location of the axis in the diagram
            \n\nThe coordinates (X_D, Y_D, Z_D) give the position of point D, which is an arbitrary point in space. 
            In the next section, it is represented as a sphere that has been attatched to the wall.
        </text>

